answers.name: Bradycardia: Baseline Fetal Heart Rate: (FHR less than 80 bpm for more than 10minutes), heart rate that does not return to normal
Late deceleration in the Fetal Heart Rate (at the end of contraction FHR less than 80 bpm) repeated for 30 minutes
Dynamic dystocia (cervical dilatation not responding to any treatment)
Fetal presentation abnormalities ( Shoulder or transverse)
Chorioamnionitis ((T* > 39*C, Foulsmelling vaginal discharge, and uterine tenderness outside contractions))

Severe pre-eclampsia (severe proteinuria > 5g/24h and/or persistent high blood pressure, DBP > 110mmHg resistant to antihypertensive therapy. A fortiori with one or more of the following symptoms: persistent headache, blurred vision, epigastric pain, marked hyperreflexia.)
Fetal Heart rate abnormalities (Fetal tachycardia (Persistent FHR>180 bpm >1 hour after reducing maternal hyperthermia with paracetamol and antibiotics))
Fetal Heart rate abnormalities (Regular and late deceleration of FHR <90 bpm for one hour)
History of 2 or more previous C/S/ Uterine rupture
General condition of the mother (cardio-neuro-pulmonary insufficiency)
